{"key":"post-12817711","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12817711</id>\n<content>To the OP, you can add gypsum to the soak, or as a pinch later when you load the jars.&amp;nbsp; I prefer to add it to the soak water, but as long as you get some gypsum in there, you're fine.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Without a picture it's hard to diagnose the problem.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;To Javadog, a 1/4&quot; hole is way too big for jar lids.&amp;nbsp; Use four 1/16&quot; holes and the grains won't ever touch your filter.&amp;nbsp; The 'greasy' appearance you're talking about is bacteria contamination.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;An important thing to remember is if you shake a grain jar and it doesn't recover, it was already contaminated prior to the shake.&amp;nbsp; The shake won't cause it.&amp;nbsp; Also, don't fill jars more than 2/3 full to allow breathing air space for the mycelium, and shaking room for later.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12818061</next>\n<prev>12817133</prev>\n<first>12816585</first>\n<last>12820884</last>\n<when>1277750027</when>\n<utime>06/28/10 09:33 PM</utime>\n</post>"}